speechtext:
The PRIME MINISTER (Rt. Hon. Sir Wilfrid Laurier) moved that to-morrow the House go into Committee of the Whole on the following resolution ;
That it is expedient to provide that, after July 1st, 1902, one-half of the net proceeds of all taxes paid by Chinese immigrants shall, at the end of every fiscal year, be paid to the province wherein they were collected.
Motion agreed to.

I understood the Postmaster General to say, in reply to the question as to whether he has made provision for the employment of a larger number of 122}
letter carriers, that he is going to ask for tenders for the collection of street letter boxes, and that the men who are now engaged in that work will be available to act as letter carriers. There will probably be eight or ten of these men available for that purpose, but so far as I can gather, that number is entirely inadequate. If the hon. gentleman will examine internally the Toronto post office, he will find that it is the biggest sweating shop in Canada.
The hon. member for Selkirk said that merchants from Winnipeg have to wait from four to five hours after the mails are received in the general post office, before they are delivered by the carriers. Well, it is a fact that merchants in Toronto send their messengers to the side door of the post office to get their mails rather than wait until the over-burdened letter carrier is able to reach them.
